close_symbols: struct lfs_t (fields: cfg, rcache, seed, block_count, gdisk)
struct lfs_mdir_t (fields: pair, rev, off, etag, count, tail, split, erased)
callback cb semantics / return codes (negative error, LFS_CMP_EQ, LFS_CMP_GT)
explanation:
To decide if any executed operation in lfs_dir_fetchmatch is dead (i.e. removable without changing program behaviour) the analyzer must know the semantics, side-effects and possible return values of every external symbol and the layout of data the function manipulates. Brief reasons by symbol/group:

- lfs_bd_read: reads blocks/tags and returns errors; must know if reads have side-effects (caches) or error semantics that make earlier reads necessary.
- lfs_bd_crc: computes/crc-checks ranges and returns errors; influences control-flow and erased detection.
- lfs_fromle32 / lfs_frombe32 / lfs_tole32: byte-order conversion used on rev, tag, fcrc; removing calls could change values and behaviour.
- lfs_crc: updates CRC and lfs->seed; has side-effect (seed mix) so its calls may be non-dead.
- lfs_tag_dsize / lfs_tag_size / lfs_tag_isdelete: determine tag length/off advances; necessary to see whether off computations and subsequent reads are required.
- lfs_tag_isvalid / lfs_tag_type1 / lfs_tag_type2 / lfs_tag_type3 / lfs_tag_chunk / lfs_tag_id / lfs_tag_splice: tag decoding predicates that affect control-flow and modifications of temp state (tempcount, tempbesttag, tempsplit, etc.). Their semantics decide whether branches/assignments are live.
- LFS_MKTAG, LFS_CMP_EQ, LFS_CMP_GT: tag construction and callback comparison constants used in comparisons that determine updates to tempbesttag and returns; needed to know if those updates are meaningful.
- LFS_ERR_CORRUPT, LFS_ERR_NOENT, LFS_BLOCK_NULL: error and sentinel constants used in returns and initializations; needed to determine whether certain return/assignment statements are reachable/useful.
- LFS_TYPE_CCRC / LFS_TYPE_NAME / LFS_TYPE_SPLICE / LFS_TYPE_TAIL / LFS_TYPE_FCRC: concrete tag type values used in many branches; must know which branches are possible and consequential.
- lfs_pair_fromle32 / lfs_pair_swap: pair byte-order and swap ops that affect which block is scanned; removing them could change which block is used.
- lfs_gstate_hasmovehere and lfs_pair_cmp: synthetic move detection that mutates besttag; must know its semantics to decide if related adjustments are necessary.
- lfs_min: used to compute *id from besttag and dir->count; needed to know if assignment to *id is required.
- lfs_fcrc_fromle32 and struct lfs_fcrc (fields size, crc): used for erased detection; necessary to determine whether fcrc checks and related reads are needed.
- lfs_fs_disk_version and LFS_MULTIVERSION macro: conditional compilation and version checks change erased-detection behaviour; required to know if that code path is compiled/active.
- struct lfs_t (cfg, rcache, seed, block_count, gdisk): layout and side-effects on lfs state (seed update, block_count protects corruption check, gdisk/tag used by synthetic move) are required to decide whether writes to lfs fields are meaningful.
- struct lfs_mdir_t (pair, rev, off, etag, count, tail, split, erased): the function writes many fields of dir; to know if those writes are dead requires the mdir layout and whether callers read them later.
- struct lfs_config (block_size, prog_size): used to bound reads and check erased-prog alignment; influences control-flow and whether certain CRC checks are required.
- callback cb semantics / return codes: cb may have side-effects; its return values (negative errors, LFS_CMP_EQ, LFS_CMP_GT) alter tempbesttag and control-flow. To decide if calling cb (and related tag comparison logic) is dead requires cb contract (effects of removing calls).

In short: to determine whether any executed operation in lfs_dir_fetchmatch can be removed without changing program behaviour, the analyzer must know the exact semantics, side-effects and return/error behaviours of all I/O/CRC/tag decoding routines, the macros/constants used in branching, struct layouts and whether fields written by this function are later observed by callers. The symbols above are the minimal set required to make that determination.
